Problem Statement: Card games such as blackjack and poker require players to make sequential decisions under
uncertainty. Most players rely on memorized heuristics or intuition rather than rigorous probability analysis, leading
to suboptimal decisions. The primary users of our system are casual or intermediate players who want to improve
their strategic decision-making but cannot calculate probabilities, expected value, or opponent behavior in real time.
In blackjack, players must choose actions such as hit, stand, double, or split without knowing future cards. In poker,
players must reason about hidden information and infer opponents’ hands from observed actions. Current approaches
such as static strategy charts or simple card counting fail to adapt dynamically to changing game states. This creates
an opportunity for an AI system that can analyze probabilities, enumerate outcomes, and recommend the action with
the highest expected value.


Why Now? Recent advances in machine learning, probabilistic modeling, and simulation make real-time strategic
analysis feasible. Modern AI systems can efficiently simulate large numbers of game outcomes and update probability
estimates as new information becomes available. In addition, publicly available datasets and simulation environments
allow models to be trained on millions of synthetic poker and blackjack hands. Increased computing power enables
near real-time evaluation of expected value, making AI-assisted decision support systems practical for complex strategic
games. Over the next several years, systems that combine probabilistic reasoning and machine learning will become
increasingly important in domains requiring decision-making under uncertainty.


Proposed AI-Powered Solution: We propose an AI-driven system that evaluates the current game state and recommends the action with the highest expected value (EV). For blackjack, the model will simulate possible future card
outcomes and compute EV for each action using
EV = P(win)W + P(push) · 0 − P(lose)L
allowing the system to recommend the optimal decision given the remaining deck composition. For poker, the system
will use Bayesian inference to estimate opponent hand probabilities from observed actions:
P(hand | action) = P(action | hand)P(hand)
P(action) .
By updating these probabilities after each betting action, the model can estimate win probabilities and evaluate whether
a player should fold, call, or raise. AI provides value beyond rule-based strategies by dynamically updating probabilities,
modeling opponent behavior, and evaluating many potential outcomes through simulation.


Initial Technical Concept: The system will primarily rely on simulated gameplay data rather than real casino data.
Millions of blackjack and poker hands can be generated to train and evaluate the models. Blackjack decisions will be
evaluated through probabilistic simulation and expected value calculations based on deck composition and player/dealer
states. Poker modeling will focus on estimating opponent hand distributions and updating beliefs using Bayesian
inference. Potential techniques include Monte Carlo simulation for expected value estimation, reinforcement learning
agents trained through self-play, and probabilistic classifiers for opponent modeling. Our nanoGPT component could be
used to generate natural-language explanations of recommended strategies, helping users understand why a particular
decision maximizes expected value.

Scope for MVP: Within approximately six weeks, we plan to build a minimum viable product focused on blackjack
decision support. A user will input their hand and the dealer’s visible card, and the system will compute and return the
recommended action along with the estimated expected value. This demonstrates the core AI capability of enumerating
outcomes and selecting the optimal decision. A simplified poker prototype may also be implemented where the system
estimates opponent hand probabilities based on observed actions.


Risks and Open Questions: Several uncertainties remain. Modeling opponent behavior in poker may require simplifying assumptions that limit realism. Evaluation metrics must ensure that the AI recommendations outperform
baseline strategies such as standard blackjack charts. Finally, usability is an open question; the system must present
recommendations clearly without requiring excessive manual input from the user.
